Sonic49 | ??? 24-May-21 11:46 AM
I suppose we should clear one thing up - this area is still inside the airship. Just less so. This room is more or less a glorified balcony - the section itself is extending from the airship, but what would be the 'fresh' air is covered by windows (probably for safety purposes, as air high above would not be pleasant, to say the least), meaning the whole room's effectively a glass box with a solid bottom (good enough). It's also rather wide. A couple of chairs and tables, similar to the ones in the lounge, are here, allowing you to sit back and watch the rather beautiful outside view. There's also a couple of potted plants to the side, fitting the more 'outdoorsy' vibe this place has. There's also a weird blue button on the wall perpendicular to the door, but it does nothing. Odd. Kojima Akihiro | Mass 06-Jun-21 07:57 PM
What a day, what a day. By all rights, what happened today should've been ridiculously stress-inducing, delirium might've been a possible route for those fragile enough to be overwhelmed by such a thing. The same can't be said about Akihiro though. Shaken after everything that's happened is practically a given but his mind and body were pumped full of adrenaline after the revelation of their purpose here and the sudden explosion that ensued moments later after someone tried to test the waters. Most important of all, Akihiro was...exhilarated. He couldn't express all of this in the heat of the moment due to how fast-paced everything was going but he could feel the pounding of his heart going increasingly fast with every second he spent there in the meeting room. "Whatever pantheon that sits atop the heavens have blessed me once again, for this is an opportunity." Indeed. An opportunity. One he so desperately sought after once he was established as an Ultimate. It was almost perfect all he could do was laugh his heart out. And so he did. From a quiet chuckle to a full on maniacal cackle, he tried to relish in this position Drake has put him in and what he intends to do with it.

If the fire were still there, she would have wanted to put it out, despite always struggling to do so. Ba-dump. Ba-dump. Ba-dump. Ba-dump. . . . twelve. That's twelve times she listened to her heart pound individually; to the beat of its own drum. She could survive this motive if nothing disturbs its rhythm. It was the only sound that could lull her. It was the only noise that kept her sane . . . from herself. Ba-dump . . . Ba-dump . . . Ba-dump . . . 'Ba-dump.'

For no longer could she hear her heartbeat . . . For no longer did she feel safe in this room. The entity chuckled, clearly satisfied with her reaction.
